{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631591"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:29:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:29:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17384"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17384"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10074"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115116"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10074"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17384"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97124"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7752"},{"type":"tags","id":"7812"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23581"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115116"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team is designing a clinical trial to test a new treatment for hypertension. They are discussing the statistical considerations for their study design.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a Type I error in statistical hypothesis testing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis","Failing to reject a false null hypothesis","Rejecting a true null hypothesis","Rejecting both null and alternative hypotheses","Correctly accepting a true null hypothesis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EType I error\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when we reject a null hypothesis that is actually true. This is also known as a false positive. The probability of making a Type I error is denoted by alpha (\u03b1), which is typically set at 0.05.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFailing to reject a false null hypothesis\u003C/strong\u003E represents a Type II error (false negative). \u003Cstrong\u003ECorrectly rejecting a false null hypothesis\u003C/strong\u003E represents statistical power (1 - \u03b2). \u003Cstrong\u003ECorrectly accepting a true null hypothesis\u003C/strong\u003E represents a true negative. \u003Cstrong\u003ERejecting both null and alternative hypotheses\u003C/strong\u003E is not possible as the hypotheses are mutually exclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding Type I errors is crucial for research design as it helps determine appropriate sample sizes and significance levels. The conventional significance level of 0.05 means we accept a 5% chance of making a Type I error.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type I errors (false positives) occur when rejecting a true null hypothesis.","Type II errors (false negatives) occur when failing to reject a false null hypothesis.","Statistical power is the probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis (1 - probability of Type II error)."],"references":["Motulsky H. Intuitive Biostatistics: A Nonmathematical Guide to Statistical Thinking. 4th ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press; 2017. Chapter 16; pg. 148.","Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97124"}},"question":{"data":{"t